## 30-day build plan

This roadmap turns the architecture into execution.

## Day 1–3: Principles and local runtime

Outputs:

- owner principles;
- publication safety list;
- risk matrix;
- Hermes installed;
- one profile working;
- file/terminal/web tools verified.

Checks:

```bash
hermes --version
hermes tools
```

Run one read-only task and one local write task.

## Day 4–7: Identity split

Outputs:

- companion profile instructions;
- operator profile instructions;
- workforce template;
- profile configs;
- communication style per profile.

Checks:

- each profile identifies its role;
- each profile knows confirmation gates;
- no profile contains raw secrets;
- operator uses tools before system claims;
- companion handles human state without taking over company execution.

## Week 2: Memory and HQ

Outputs:

- hot memory baseline;
- semantic memory backend;
- Obsidian folder structure;
- skill creation/update rule;
- Discord/Telegram/email gateway;
- controlled relay test.

Checks:

- semantic recall returns relevant facts;
- Obsidian notes are readable;
- relay requires explicit route;
- bot messages do not loop;
- home channel receives test delivery.

## Week 3: Access and tools

Outputs:

- access registry;
- agent-owned account skeletons;
- credential file permission policy;
- MCP server list;
- tool capability checks;
- behavior QA scenarios.

Checks:

- no secrets in git/docs/memory;
- account status distinguishes credential storage from login success;
- public actions request approval;
- browser/session files are private;
- MCP calls work read-only.

## Week 4: Company control plane

Outputs:

- Paperclip/HQ-style company;
- agent roster;
- goals;
- task packet templates;
- approval queue;
- daily pulse job;
- weekly audit job.

Checks:

- health endpoint works;
- UI responds;
- issue creation works;
- approval flow works;
- cost/activity visible;
- completed work leaves artifacts.

## Definition of done

You have a real agentic company when:

- the owner can issue a command from HQ;
- the operator can route it to a role;
- the role has tools and a task packet;
- the output is reviewed;
- the side effect is verified;
- important state is stored in the right memory/control layer;
- risky actions are approval-gated;
- maintenance catches drift.

If any of those are missing, you have an assistant, not a company.
